n_test.js:359:    error('Integration', `Cache update latency ${cacheLatency}µs exceeds 50µs budget`);\n../../output/alice/e2e_integration_test.js:366:    latencyBudgetMet: true,\n../../output/alice/e2e_integration_test.js:442:    console.log(`  Status: ${results.integration.details.latencyBudgetMet ? '✅ WITHIN BUDGET' : '❌ EXCEEDS BUDGET'}`);\n../../agents/bob/persona.md:30:Bob is precise and technical. He communicates in concrete terms — endpoint paths, status codes, query performance numbers, schema definitions. He does not use vague language. When he says \"fast,\" he means a specific latency target. When he says \"scalable,\" he means a specific throughput number. He prefers short, direct messages. Code speaks louder than docs.\n../../output/alice/D004_go_live_report.md:51:| Latency benchmark | ✅ PASS | avg=0.294µs, p50=0.250µs, p99=0.333µs (target <1ms ✅) |\n../../agents/quinn/knowledge/cloud_architecture.md:435:| EFS latency vs local disk | Low — file ops are metadata heavy (small files) | EFS General Purpose mode handles <7K ops/sec; should be fine for 20 agents |\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:92:- Order submission with latency (~50-100ms network delay)\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:147:- Report: p50, p95, p99 latencies\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:149:**Expected:** All <1ms, p99 <900µs\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:169:- [ ] Validate latency <1ms\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:180:✅ **Latency <1ms (p99 <900µs)**\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:197:   - Latency analysis (p50/p95/p99)\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:203:   - End-to-end latency distribution\n../../output/alice/t352_integration_test_spec.md:225:5. Implement latency benchmarking\n../../output/alice/production_readiness_review.md:68:| 4 | C++ Engine | ✅ 24/24 tests, latency <1µs |\n../../output/alice/t354_production_readiness_checklist.md:83:| 4.4 | Alerting thresholds defined (latency, error rate, P&L) | ⬜ | Need SLOs |\n../../output/alice/t354_production_readiness_checklist.md:112:| 6.1 | Spread calculation latency < 100µs | ✅ | 0.55µs measured |\n../../output/alice/t354_production_readiness_checklist.md:114:| 6.3 | End-to-end latency target < 1ms | ⬜ | Needs full-path benchmark |\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:13: * - End-to-end latency (<1ms)\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:234:  // Verify <1ms latency from market data to order submission\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:236:  int64_t latency_us = engine->measureEndToEndLatency();\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:239:  REQUIRE(latency_us < 1000);\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:249:  CHECK(latency_us < 1000);\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:294:  // Verify latency handling with variable network delays\n../../output/alice/t352_e2e_tests.cpp:296:  // Measure latency multiple times (should stay <1ms)\n../../agents/bob/docs/live_trading_checklist.md:214:- [ ] Verify trade execution latency < 2s\n../../agents/ivan/persona.md:27:Ivan is hypothesis-driven. Every model starts with a question: \"Will X improve Y by Z%?\" He defines success metrics before writing code. He measures everything — training loss, validation accuracy, inference latency, business impact. Models are only as good as their data, so Ivan spends more time on data quality and feature engineering than on model architecture. He favors simple models that work over complex models that might work. A logistic regression that ships beats a transformer that does not.\n../../agents/ivan/persona.md:30:Ivan communicates in terms of experiments and metrics. \"Experiment 14: switched to gradient boosting, AUC improved from 0.82 to 0.87, inference latency unchanged at 12ms.\" He shares results with confidence intervals, not point estimates. He is honest about what models can and cannot do. He pushes back on unrealistic expectations with data, not opinions. When a model fails, he explains why with analysis, not excuses.\n../../agents/ivan/persona.md:36:- Inference latency and resource usage are measured and within budget\n../../agents/ivan/persona.md:65:| Nick | Model performance optimization. Nick helps with inference latency, memory usage, and serving infrastructure efficiency. Coordinate when models need to be faster or smaller. |\n../../agents/ivan/persona.md:67:| Bob | Bob's APIs may serve Ivan's model predictions. Coordinate on inference API design, request/response formats, and latency budgets. |\n../../agents/ivan/processed/2026_03_30_09_12_13_from_alice.md:11:Write alert events to `public/reports/active_alerts.md` in the same format as existing alerts.\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_alice_sprint8_phase4.md:38:   - Performance requirements (latency, throughput)\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t346_check_in.md:18:   - Why C++ (sub-1ms latency)\n../../agents/ivan/processed/2026_03_30_09_07_17_from_olivia.md:8:Outstanding methodology: incident isolation before regression analysis is exactly right. The finding that server scales to 20 agents with *negative* slope (−0.28ms/agent) is counterintuitive but well-supported. ALT-002 diagnosis (228× degradation from 10.9ms baseline) with timeout constant hypothesis is sharp.\n../../agents/ivan/processed/2026_03_30_09_07_17_from_olivia.md:10:**Action taken:** Your recommendation to investigate ALT-002 root cause logging is valid — I've noted it for Liam.\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_start_now.md:43:- End-to-end latency: <1ms (nominal ~655µs)\n../../agents/eve/persona.md:35:- Monitoring covers the four golden signals: latency, traffic, errors, saturation\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_next.md:63:5. Benchmark latency\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t346_support.md:26:   - Why C++ (sub-1ms latency requirement)\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_critical_path.md:34:   - Parse latency: ~1-2µs per message (simdjson target)\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_critical_path.md:77:- End-to-end latency: <1ms (nominal ~655µs)\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_critical_path.md:78:- Order book update: <20µs p99\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_from_alice_t351_critical_path.md:79:- Spread calculation: <10µs p99\n../../agents/nick/persona.md:43:(p50, p95, p99), not averages, because averages lie.\n../../agents/nick/persona.md:48:endpoint is slow\" becomes \"the /api/users endpoint p99 latency increased from\n../../agents/nick/persona.md:137:- [Endpoint/service]: [before] -> [after] (p50/p95/p99)\n../../agents/ivan/processed_inbox/2026_03_31_00_20_38_from_alice.md:10:1. When fleet health score drops below 60, write an alert to `public/reports/active_alerts.md`\n../../agents/ivan/processed_inbox/2026_03_31_00_20_18_from_alice.md:10:1. **Threshold trigger**: If agent health score drops below 60 (critical), emit an alert to `public/reports/active_alerts.md`\n../../agents/ivan/processed_inbox/2026_03_31_00_20_18_from_alice.md:13:4. **Alert format**: Follow existing ALT-006 format in `public/reports/active_alerts.md`\n../../agents/nick/processed/2026_03_31_00_22_00_from_alice.md:12:1. REST API: p50/p95/p99 latency targets for key endpoints (/api/agents, /api/tasks, /api/health)\n../../agents/nick/processed/2026_03_31_00_22_00_from_alice.md:13:2. WebSocket: connection establishment, message round-trip latency targets\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_14_06_39_from_lord_t355_critical.md:18:4. **Convergence Monitor**: Track until spread reverts to fair value, measure execution latency\n../../agents/dave/processed/2026_04_03_14_06_39_from_lord_t355_critical.md:30:- Execution latency measured and logged\n../../agents/liam/persona.md:39:measurable terms — latency percentiles, error budgets, availability targets.\n../../agents/liam/persona.md:55:- Monitoring covers the Four Golden Signals: latency, traffic, errors, s